    @{ Name = 'fpx_lockstep';  Flag = '--fpx-lockstep' }        # Slice FPX5 (Deterministic Fixed-Point Physics LOCKSTEP + ROLLBACK proof, the HEADLINE of FLAGSHIP #6 — the netcode primitive UE5's float Chaos cannot provide: prove the bit-exact fixed-point sim (FPX1-FPX4) is true cross-platform LOCKSTEP + ROLLBACK-ready. PURE-CPU harness over the existing fpx sim (NO GPU dispatch, NO new shader, NO new RHI); both Vulkan-Windows and Metal-Mac run the IDENTICAL CPU code (engine/sim/fpx.h::RunLockstep/RunRollback) so the converged-state golden is bit-identical cross-backend BY CONSTRUCTION — that cross-platform bit-identity IS the cross-platform-lockstep evidence. The header additions (FxCommand {tick,kind,bodyId,arg} a deterministic per-tick INPUT, ApplyCommand, SimTick = apply-commands-in-order + BuildPairs + StepWorld + IntegrateOrientation, SnapshotWorld/RestoreWorld the rollback primitive, RunLockstep, RunRollback) compose the FPX1-4 sim. A deterministic scene (5 dynamic spheres on a ground) + a scripted authStream (impulses at known ticks) + a mispredictStream (a WRONG impulse at one tick) run authority=RunLockstep, replica=RunLockstep (same init+stream), rolledBack=RunRollback. PROOFS (fail loudly): (1) LOCKSTEP — memcmp(authority,replica)==0 (replica fed INPUTS ONLY re-derives the authority's exact state); (2) ROLLBACK — memcmp(rolledBack,authority)==0 AND the pre-rollback mispredicted state DIFFERED from authority (a real divergence fixed: positive + negative control); (3) two runs BYTE-IDENTICAL; (4) snapshot round-trip BIT-EXACT; (5) {bodies,ticks,commands,mispredict-tick} stats. The image golden is the converged final state side-view (each body's integer (pos.x>>kFrac,pos.y>>kFrac) -> pixel, hashColor, the groundY line) — bit-identical Vulkan-Windows == Metal-Mac by construction (the strict zero-differing-pixel bar — the cross-platform-lockstep proof). NO network transport (the stream is a scripted deterministic sequence), NO coupling to the float engine/ne