    @{ Name = 'fpx_solve';     Flag = '--fpx-solve' }           # Slice FPX3 (Deterministic Fixed-Point Physics PBD POSITIONAL collision-response solver, the MAKE-OR-BREAK of FLAGSHIP #6 — resolves collisions in FIXED-POINT so overlapping bodies push apart + rest on the ground into a settled PILE, proven GPU==CPU BIT-EXACT, frame-deterministic, cross-backend. A PBD positional solver: for each CONTACT (body-vs-ground or a penetrating sphere-sphere pair from FPX2's BuildPairs) move the two bodies apart along the contact normal by their inverse-mass-weighted share of the penetration depth — purely POSITIONAL (NO velocity impulses/restitution), run on a SINGLE THREAD ([numthreads(1,1,1)], sequential Gauss-Seidel = bit-exact). The integer core extends engine/sim/fpx.h: fxdiv ((a<<kFrac)/b Q16.16 truncating divide via int64 shift), FxNormalize (integer normalize via FxLength's FxISqrt, NO std::sqrt), ResolveGround/ResolvePair, SolveContacts (K iters, ground then pairs in the FIXED FPX2 order) + StepWorld = IntegrateStep + SolveContacts. A deterministic CLUSTER (a 6x6 loose stack, radii so neighbors collide, gravity (0,-9.8,0), groundY=0, dt=kOne/60) is stepped K=180 (solveIters=8) by shaders/fpx_solve.comp — a single thread runs each step, the math copied VERBATIM from fpx.h, writing gBodies back; the pair list is built ONCE on the host + uploaded. ReadBuffer reads the integer body array, PROVEN BIT-EXACT vs the CPU fpx.h::StepWorld reference (memcmp, NO tol — the GPU==CPU make-or-break), {bodies, contacts, residual-overlap (deterministic, not necessarily 0), above-ground}, a hand-checked contact, solveEnabled=false -> bodies UNCHANGED no-op, two runs byte-identical; the image golden is a PURE-INTEGER settled-pile side-view — identical both backends by construction. Because fxdiv/FxISqrt use int64, fpx_solve.comp is VULKAN-SPIR-V-ONLY (DXC compiles int64; glslc cannot) and the Metal --fpx-solve runs the CPU StepWorld (byte-identical by construction, the fpx_integrate.comp